<h4>Step 1</h4>

{{template "instructions-rpi-step1.tmpl" .}}

<p>(Optional) The device can run as a local web server.  To enable, specify a port to listen on.  The device's address is http://addr:port, where addr is the local IP (or hostname).  This is useful, for example, when the hub is not accessible, and you want to check in on the device.</p>

<h4>Step 2</h4>

<p>Click the Download button to download the demo installer file.  The installer file name is:</p>

<pre>
<code>
	{{.Device.Model}}-{{.Device.Id}}-installer
</code>
</pre>

<h4>Step 3 (Optional)</h4>

<p>Verify the MD5 checksum:</p>

<pre>
<code>
	$ md5sum {{.Device.Model}}-{{.Device.Id}}-installer
</code>
</pre>

<h4>Step 4</h4>

<p>Copy the installer file to the Raspberry Pi system and run:</p>

<pre>
<code>
	$ chmod +x {{.Device.Model}}-{{.Device.Id}}-installer
	$ sudo ./{{.Device.Model}}-{{.Device.Id}}-installer

	Intalling {{.Device.Model}}-{{.Device.Id}}...
	Intalling logging for {{.Device.Model}}-{{.Device.Id}}...
	Intalling systemd service for {{.Device.Model}}-{{.Device.Id}}...
	Success!
</code>
</pre>

<p>The installer will install the device as a service named "{{.Device.Model}}-{{.Device.Id}}".  To uninstall:</p>

<pre>
<code>
	$ sudo ./{{.Device.Model}}-{{.Device.Id}}-installer -u
</code>
</pre>

<p>To view device logs:</p>

<pre>
<code>
	$ sudo tail -f /var/log/{{.Device.Model}}-{{.Device.Id}}.log
</code>
</p>
